# Cloudflare Pages custom headers.
#
# v0.6.2: force `sw.js` to always revalidate. CF Pages' default
# cache-control on static files is `public, max-age=14400,
# must-revalidate` — a 4-hour edge/browser cache. That's fine for
# content-hashed chunks (their URLs change per release) and for icons,
# but WRONG for the service worker: `reg.update()` (fired by the
# in-app "Check for updates" button and periodic auto-check) fetches
# /sw.js, byte-compares to the running SW, and installs a new one on
# diff. If the browser returns a 4-hour-cached copy of the OLD sw.js,
# there IS no diff — update silently skipped. Brooks hit this after
# the v0.6.0 → v0.6.1 deploy: "checking for updates" reported he was
# current at v0.6.0 for an hour, because the browser was serving the
# old sw.js from HTTP cache.
#
# no-cache doesn't mean "don't cache" — it means "always revalidate
# with the origin". Perfect for a small file that gates the whole
# update pipeline.
/sw.js
  Cache-Control: no-cache
